  "prompt": "How do you choose an unresponsive yoyo?",
  "response": "When choosing an unresponsive yoyo, consider the following factors:\n\n1. Skill level\n- Recommended for intermediate to advanced players\n- Requires specific throwing techniques and bind return\n\n2. Material\n- Metal: Typically more durable and stable\n- Plastic: Lighter and more affordable\n- Hybrid: Combination of materials\n\n3. Shape\n- Butterfly shape: Good for string tricks\n- Modified shape: Better for looping tricks\n- V-shape: More stable for advanced techniques\n\n4. Bearing type\n- Size C bearing: Standard for most unresponsive yoyos\n- Center track bearing: Reduces string friction\n- Flat bearing: Provides different play characteristics\n\n5. Width and diameter\n- Wider yoyos: More stable\n- Larger diameter: Slower spin\n- Smaller diameter: Faster spin\n\n6. Weight\n- Heavier: More stable, slower\n- Lighter: Faster, more agile\n\n7. Budget\n- Entry-level unresponsive: $20-$50\n- Professional models: $50-$200\n\n8. Brand reputation\n- Duncan\n- YoYoFactory\n- C3yoyodesign\n- OneDrop\n\nConsider your skill level, budget, and intended play style when selecting an unresponsive yoyo.",
